# Static assets — 404 instead of HTML fallback.
# When the SPA catch-all serves index.html for a missing JS/CSS file, the browser
# receives text/html but expects application/javascript or text/css. Strict MIME
# type checking then blocks the resource with "Expected a JavaScript module but
# the server responded with a MIME type of text/html". Returning 404 is the correct
# behavior — it lets the browser (and our error boundary) surface a clear error
# instead of a cryptic MIME type failure.
# These rules only trigger when the file doesnʼt exist on disk; existing assets
# are served directly by Cloudflare Pages.
/assets/*.js      /404.html   404
/assets/*.css     /404.html   404
/assets/*.woff2   /404.html   404

# Root-level JS/CSS — same reasoning as /assets/ above (service worker, init scripts, etc.)
/*.js             /404.html   404
/*.css            /404.html   404

# Cloudflare Pages SPA fallback.
# Without this, direct navigation to client-side routes (e.g. /courses) 404s
# because the static host tries to resolve them as files before React Router
# can handle them. The `200` status is critical — using 301/302 breaks deep
# links by changing the URL. Asset paths are excluded above so only actual
# SPA routes get the fallback.
/*    /index.html   200
